the pharaonic traditions of Egypt as well as earlier Greek poetry, this book affords unique insight into how praise poetry for Ptolemy and his wife may have helped to negotiate the adaptation of Greek culture that changed conditions of the new Hellenistic world. Invaluable for its clear translation and its commentary on genre, dialect, diction, and historical reference in relation to Theocritus's Encomium, the book is also significant for what it reveals about the poem's cultural and social contexts and about Theocritus' devices for addressing his several readerships.COVER IMAGE: The image on the front cover of this book is incorrectly identified on the jacket flap. The correct caption is: Gold Oktadrachm depicting Ptolemy II and Arsinoe (mid-third century BCE; by permission of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aalexandria.  aancient egypt.  aancient greece.  aaristophanes.  aarsinoe ii.  aart.  aaugustan poetry.  aclassical studies.  aclouds.  aegypt.  aencomium.  agenre studies.  agreek culture.  agreek poetry.  agreek world.  ahellenism.  ahellenistic poetry.  ahellenistic world.  aheracles.  ahomeric hymn.  ahymn.  aking.  alatin poetry.  aliterary criticism.  amonarchy.  amythology.  apatronage.  apatrons.  apharaoh.  apharaonic traditions.  aphiladelphus.  apithom stele.  apoetic meter.  apoetic tribute.  apoetry.  apoets.  apraise.  aptolemaic dynasty.  aptolemy ii.  areign.  aruler.  atheocritus.  athird century.  azeus.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023560140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092937140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97